frameDefinitions: A Wearer removes an item of Clothing from a Body_location (the part of the body that the Clothing is prototypically worn on.)
An Agent causes a Theme to move away from a location, the Source.
An Agent is performing the portion of an Activity in which there is dynamic stability. ''
The words in this frame describe the 'fictive' motion of a stationary Road.
A Wearer puts on an item of Clothing, which then occupies the Body_location.
These are words describing situations in which a Perpetrator takes Goods from a  Victim or a Source.
frameExamples: Walking on sand is better if you <t>take</t> <t>off</t> your shoes. INI
I saw that several men in dark suits had <t>removed</t> all of the evidence from the scene.
Not noticing the hoards of people rushing by the window, Manny <t>continued</t> eating his lunch.
The long mountain road <t>meandered</t> through the woods.
You didn't have to <t>dress</t> like a pirate to impress me. INI
I can't believe he <t>pickpocketed</t> my gold watch !
listRoleDefinitions: The individual who begins the action wearing the <fen>Clothing</fen> and ends the action without it.
The item that the <fen>Wearer</fen> is initially wearing but then removes.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which a <fen>Wearer</fen> undresses.
The location at which the <fen>Wearer</fen> undresses an item of <fen>Clothing</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person (or other force) that causes the <fen>Theme</fen> to move.
Theme is the object that changes location.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the initial location of the <fen>Theme</fen>, before it changes location.
The non-Agentive cause of the removing event.
The time at which the removal takes place.
The location where the removal takes place.

Duration denotes the length of <fen>Time</fen> from the beginning of a continuous situation (the one denoted by the target) to its end. In many cases, the continuous situation is a dynamic action which is ongoing, while in others it is simply an undifferentiated state.
This role identifies the name of the ongoing <fen>Activity</fen> in which an <fen>Agent</fen> engages.
The <fen>Agent</fen> engages in an ongoing <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when an ongoing <fen>Activity</fen> occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the ongoing <fen>Activity</fen> occurs.

Any expression which implies a definite starting-point of the <fen>Road</fen>. In prepositional phrases, the prepositional object expresses the starting point of motion. In particles, the starting point of motion is understood from context.
The trajectory that would be followed by one moving on the <fen>Road</fen>.
Any expression which tells where the fictive mover travelling along a <fen>Road</fen> would end up.

A physical path that a virtual moving entity can be imagined to travel along.
<fex name='Road'>The bike trail</fex> <t>zigzagged</t> through the woods.
This frame element is used for expressions which describe a general area in which motion takes place when the motion is understood to be irregular and not to consist of a single linear path.
The configuration formed by the entire <fen>Path</fen> along the <fen>Road</fen>.
The direction in which a 'fictive' mover would travel along a <fen>Road</fen>.

The time when the fictive motion takes place.  This may describe the time when the <fen>Road</fen> or a particular piece of the <fen>Road</fen> existed, or it may implicitly describe the time when an actual motion event occurred on the <fen>Road</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the motion (which is specified by a <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen>) is located.
The individual that puts <fen>Clothing</fen> on their body.
<fen>Clothing</fen> is used for the item of clothing that the <fen>Wearer</fen> ends up wearing.
The time when the <fen>Wearer</fen> puts an item of <fen>Clothing</fen> on.
The <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the Donning occurs.
<fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) that takes the goods away.
<fen>Victim</fen> is the person (or other sentient being or group) that owns the goods before they are taken away by the perpetrator.
<fen>Goods</fen> is anything (including labor, time, or legal rights) that can be taken away.
<fen>Source</fen> is the initial location of the goods, before they change location.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the theft occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the theft occurs.
